But there is no indication of what the beginning or end of that purpose may be. Apart from organic life the docile, calculable, inorganic world seems dead. Yet we are often forced, when we least expect it, to suspect that the poetry of motion, of light and shade, colour and outline, which we perceive in inorganic. nature, is not our fiction, but something that impinges on reality only in a lesser degree than organic life itself‚ and 1s consequently akin to life, not to death.

When organic life appears upon the scene, we perceive a force more feeble according to mechanical standards, but which evinces a new complexity and a higher order of progress. It seems to have a greater degree of autonomy. Its every individual form and movement is unique, and it possesses a capacity for developing from one form to another ——from frond to leaf, from moss to tree. Whether life adapts itself to its environment, or whether the environment calls forth each adaptation, we cannot tell ; but there is progress from simple to complex, from unconsciousness to self-consciousness. Can we detect purpose? If we can it is only in the principle of natura] selection, the persistence of the fit. But we see that every step of advance brings what appears to be temporary confusion as to what apparent perfection may be.
